# Python Port Scanner

A simple CLI port/network scanner built with Scapy and sockets, for learning Python and networking.

## Requirements
- Linux
- Python 3
- Scapy (`pip install scapy --break-system-packages`)
- Root/sudo (required for arp, ping, syn, and ack scans)

## Usage
```
sudo python3 main.py -t <target> -s <scan_type> -p <ports>
```

- `-t`, `--target` (required): IP address or CIDR range (e.g. `192.168.1.1` or `192.168.1.0/24`)
- `-s`, `--scan` (optional, default: `connect`): one of `arp`, `ping`, `syn`, `connect`, `ack`
- `-p`, `--ports` (optional, default: `1-65535`): single port, list, range, or combo (e.g. `80`, `80,443`, `1-1024`)

## Examples
```
sudo python3 main.py -t 192.168.1.0/24 -s arp
sudo python3 main.py -t 192.168.1.5 -s syn -p 1-1024
sudo python3 main.py -t 192.168.1.5 -s connect -p 22,80,443
```

## Notes
- ARP and ping scans accept a CIDR range (host discovery).
- TCP scans (`connect`, `syn`, `ack`) expect a single target IP.
- See `IMPROVEMENTS.md` for known limitations.